  "diary": "Woke to that familiar Seattle patter on the windows—rain all morning, so I was grateful for the Light Rail today. The bridge closure had everyone on edge, but I lucked out with my route. Work was steady; shelved a whole cart of returns and got tangled up helping a regular track down an obscure maritime history book. Grabbed tea and a sandwich at Solstice around noon, watched the rain from the café window. Afternoon flew by between cataloging and finalizing next week's programming—we're doing a community zine workshop that I'm actually excited about. By the time I headed home, the sky was finally clearing, which felt like a small gift. Stopped at Whole Foods for herbs and rotisserie chicken, made a decent dinner. Now I'm deep in a library book about foraging in the Pacific Northwest, which feels right for a night like this. Peaceful, honestly.",
  "thought_process": "The rain and bridge closure meant I was thinking about logistics early, but the Light Rail kept things simple—no stress there. Work felt purposeful; I genuinely enjoy helping patrons find what they're looking for, and planning programming gives me agency over what the library becomes. I chose to stay near the library for lunch rather than venture out into the wet, which was practical but also reflective of my mood—I wanted containment, comfort. The programming work energized me more than usual, maybe because I'm trying to build community connections. By evening, the weather clearing matched a subtle shift in my energy. I picked up fresh herbs almost without thinking—small ritual of care. The foraging research isn't random either; it connects to something I've been mulling about lately, wanting to know the land better, understand what grows here. Felt grounded tonight.",
